title: The Grateful Dead Live at Shoreline Amphitheatre on 1993-08-27
description: Mississippi Half Step, Minglewood Blues, Lazy River Road, Broken Arrow, Eternity, Loose Lucy, Johnny B. Goode Iko Iko, Wave To The Wind, Playin' In The Band-> Uncle John's Band, Corinna, Drums-> Jam-> I Need A Miracle, The Days Between-> Throwing Stones-> Turn On Your Love Light, E: I Fought The Law

reviews.review_text: Johnny B. Goode Not a bad show. Solid throughout with the only exception that Jerry's voice is playing up a bit. A nice Wave To The Wind - the first time I have heard Jerry being able to apprehend all the chord changes in this song. Playing In The Band almost disintegrates, sounding like they are going to go into Drums before UJB. Weir even briefly starts playing the chords for Uncle John's Band AFTER Drums - maybe he forgot they already played it :-). Sound wise, there is a little weirdness in the high frequencies - almost sounding like tape wobble, but this is hardly noticable. All in all a good show, considering that (rumor has it) both Mountain Girl and Deborah Coons were backstage at this show and there were some not-so-great vibes flying around in the Garcia camp. Perhaps Bill Walton's presence cheered him up! Worth a listen.

least favorite least favorite of this Shoreline run. maybe the fact that they don't get going until Johnny B goode or is it the fact that Wave to the Wind is there. have to say. the boys crank it up starting with playing. Try nights 1 and 2 then test this one out

Lazy River..anything but lazy !? I only went to 1 GD show, fortunately I caught them my sophmore year in high school in New Orleans '88. Also 1 JGB show in Hampton '92or93. Tried to mail order tickets for the ChapelHill'94shows but w/out sucess.A guy in the nosebleed section at that N.O.show kept heckling me(but in a friendly way of course)about asking me to buy one of his homeade TieDyes. Wow, I was converted right then and there. Shortly after , picking Shrooms ensued and unlimited Perceptions were explored. Gosh , undescribable attention to the songs St.Stephen > The Eleven from Monterrey '69 ( which I picked up at one of vendors in the French Market,RockNRoll Collectibles Music Store was selling bootlegs for the public at the time ).
Anyway, this version of LazyRiverRoad is flawless with regard to passion in Jerry's voice and mixing of the bands' acoustic percussion accompaniment. For years, I was just interested in taping the long jam pleasers like Scarlet, Franklins, Eyes, etc. It's hard to believe that after all these years, I'm finally discovering the shorter ballad-like compositions that one can just sit and contemplate on their brilliance, rather than always dancing into oblivion. "Lazy" is one of those songs that puts me on a golden road instantly.  
Burners, check this one out, I think you will agree. As far as the rest of the show goes, i'm just now starting to sample the other songs. Man this website is unreal...I keep telling myself when I think of Archive.Org that Life Is Good. dave p. in New Orleans, Come to JazzFest People

Shoreline August 27 - Beautiful Moon I was at this show and as others noticed, it was low energy. Phil contributed a moving Broken Arrow which was nice. Jerry spent alot of time low on the frets. But you have to remember shows became less about a complete all night rave up and 1 or 2 songs. Days between is beautiful in any show. So many roads. The traditional material starts to not have that deep feeling. The band and jerry is tired.

That night though the sky over the penisula was crystal clear with a bright moon over the bay. It was chilly in the santa cruz mountains over the pass headed to the coast and surfing. 

So personally this show was great (not the best of the 30 so so I saw) and I enjoyed it, and yes, even the Phil Songs. But I am a fan of phil - he actually gave me a ride the Gathering of the Vibes in Bridgeport!

There are lots of shows to listen to... but you chose this one. Going purely from memory, this run peaked on the first night, and it gradually slid from there. If this show is special to you, check it out and remember the good times that were had. I'm sitting here looking at my stub right now. 102L. Unfortunately, I remember nothing about this show 31 years later, and that's because it isn't one of the better ones. I do remember the better shows that I saw in 1993 even though I was really high at most of them, and this show isn't among them. And by that I mean Jerry's playing is off. His vocals are decent for 93 though, so there is that. At least his voice isn't thrashed like it was at the end of the year. I remember that we camped up on Skyline near the 92 intersection the night before this show. There was a dirt road across the street from the parking lot on Skyline. You could drive far enough into the trees to not be visible from the road, and the view towards Half Moon Bay is spectacular from that spot. That was our go to camping spot for Shoreline since they wouldn't let you camp in the lot. What can I say about this show..... I'm sure there are highlights. It's below average for 93, but it's better than the majority of what I saw in 94-95 which is why I gave it 2 stars instead of one. It sounds like Vince blows the transition into Playin and makes it sound like a Reprise before Bob takes over with the first verse. That was weird. If you like Corrina this version into drums is pretty good, and the D/S is pretty entertaining, as were they all in the 90's with the screens, and weird people rubbing up against me. The good kind of weird, mind you. Not the other kind. Post space is full of overplayed songs that I'm not going to bother to listen to. And the IFTL caps it off with the worst encore of them all. I would rather hear Day Job than IFTL. The bottom line is that there are a lot better shows out there that are a better use of your time. Skip this one. If you MUST hear something from this run, check out set 2 from 8/25. If you want to check out a really good show from 1993, check out 5/26 at Cal Expo. I saw 42 shows in 1993 and it's the best show that I saw that year.
